// Stdlib: Geometry Conformance Traits
// Pure marker traits for characterizing the topology and geometry of bodies.
// Conformance is intended to be inferred from kernel results (volumes, faces,
// orientations) and attached as metadata; user `.ri` sources only need to
// reference these names — no fields are required for conformance.
//
// Reference: docs/reify-stdlib-reference.md §3.10. Scope: marker traits and orientation enums.
// §3.10's `Geometry` / `Transformable` supertraits and the Plane / Axis /
// BoundingBox structures (with helpers like plane_xy) are deferred to a
// follow-up task.

// ── Spatial extent ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// A body that occupies a finite region of space (bounded extent).
trait Bounded {}

// ── Topological closure ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// A body whose boundary is a closed surface (no open edges).
trait Closed {}

// A body whose boundary is a 2-manifold (every edge is shared by exactly
// two faces).
trait Manifold {}

// ── Surface orientation ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// A body whose boundary admits a consistent global outward normal.
trait Orientable {}

// ── Geometric shape ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// A body whose region is convex (every line segment between two interior
// points lies entirely within the body).
trait Convex {}

// A body whose region is path-connected (a single component).
trait Connected {}

// ── Watertightness (multi-refinement) ───────────────────────────────────────

// A body that is both Closed and Manifold — the canonical predicate for
// "watertight" geometry suitable for downstream simulation and manufacturing.
trait Watertight : Closed + Manifold {}

// ── Runtime conformance helpers (task 2320) ─────────────────────────────────
//
// Three monomorphic stdlib helpers query a body's runtime conformance:
//
//     is_watertight(g) -> Bool   — body has no open edges and a 2-manifold boundary
//     is_manifold(g)   -> Bool   — every edge is shared by exactly two faces
//     is_orientable(g) -> Bool   — boundary admits a consistent global outward normal
//
// These are recognised by name (no `fn` declarations live in this file) —
// see crates/reify-compiler/src/units.rs::GEOMETRY_QUERY_HELPER_NAMES for the
// canonical name list and crates/reify-eval/src/geometry_ops.rs::
// try_eval_conformance_query for the kernel-aware eval-time dispatch. The
// dispatch flows: compiler types the call site as `Type::Bool`, the engine's
// per-template post-process resolves the geometry-arg ValueRef against the
// realisation's named-step handle map and round-trips
// `GeometryQuery::IsWatertight | IsManifold | IsOrientable` through the
// active kernel (see crates/reify-types/src/geometry.rs for the query enum).
//
// User-assertion escape hatch: if the enclosing structure declares the
// matching marker trait, the helper short-circuits to `Bool(true)` *before*
// the kernel is consulted — pairing is one-to-one (no trait-DAG propagation):
//
//     `is_watertight` ↔ `: Watertight`
//     `is_manifold`   ↔ `: Manifold`
//     `is_orientable` ↔ `: Orientable`
//
// Note the asymmetry — declaring `: Closed + Manifold` separately does NOT
// short-circuit `is_watertight` (the runtime rule mirrors task 2321's
// per-bound `W_TRAIT_USER_ASSERTED` warning).
//
// Why no `fn` declarations: a `.ri` `fn` declaration with a body becomes a
// `CompiledFunction` and is dispatched via `eval_user_function_call` (pure
// value eval), bypassing the conformance-query surface entirely. We follow
// the same convention as constructors like `box`/`cylinder` (also recognised
// by name in `units.rs::GEOMETRY_FUNCTION_NAMES`, not declared here).

// ── Enumerations ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// The six Tait-Bryan rotation-sequence conventions accepted by orient_euler /
// orient_to_euler. Use as: orient_euler(EulerConvention.XYZ, a, b, c).
enum EulerConvention { XYZ, XZY, YXZ, YZX, ZXY, ZYX }
